            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Many microbes are free-living in the environment-in water, soil and air and on equipment-as a part of the normal microbial flora on the Earth. Most of them are not dangerous and live in peaceful symbiosis with other living beings and may also be transferred between living species, from man to animal or man to plants and environment-and vice versa [1] [2] [3] [4] [5] [6] . Microbes, like bacteria, may outnumber us by a factor of 10 22 , are heavier than us by a factor of 10 8 , have existed on Earth more than 1000 times longer than us and may undergo 500,000 generations in just one of our generations [7] .",
            "cite_spans": [
